sed","1400":"1400","after 1428":"after 1428","1374":"1374","1494":"1494","Bef 1400":"before 1400","before 1429":"before 1429","1429":"1429","1428":"1428","Aft 1429":"after 1429","Ellesborough, Buckinghamshire district, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ellesborough, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Ellesborough, Buckinghamshire, England":"Ellesborough, Buckinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Neale","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Neal  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Neal","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Old French, Anglo-Norman French, and Middle English personal name <i>Neel</i>, <i>Nele</i>, <i>Nihel</i>, <i>Niel</i>, itself derived from the Latin name <i>Nigellus</i> (a diminutive of Latin <i>niger</i> ‘black’), originally a nickname for someone with black hair or a dark complexion. The name was very common among Normans and was brought to England at the time of the Norman Conquest. There has been considerable confusion with the Irish and Scottish Gaelic name <i>Niall</i> (see   Neil  ); the two names are now pronounced identically. It is theoretically possible that in Normandy, where the personal name was popular, that it was also used for Old Norse <i>Njáll</i>, but this is difficult to prove. <i>Njáll</i> was adopted from the Irish Gaelic personal name <i>Niall</i> by Vikings in Ireland, who took it back to Iceland and Norway, but whether the Vikings also took <i>Njáll</i> to Normandy and to the northwest of England, is an open question, which cannot be settled on the available evidence.","English: alternatively from the Middle English personal name <i>Nele</i>, a variant of   Nell   as a pet form of <i>Elias</i> (see   Ellis  ). Compare   Nelson  ,   Nielson  .","Scottish and Irish: shortened form of   McNeal   (see   McNeil  )."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Neale was born in 1400, in Ellesborough, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Thomas Neale and Mrs Thomas Neale. He married Johanna Thomas before 1429, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 1429."},"et":{"1400–Aft 1429":"1400–pärast 1429","1400–1429":"1400–1429","1400–1494":"1400–1494","1429–1494":"1429–1494","1374–1428":"1374–1428","–Female":"Surnud","1400":"1400","after 1428":"pärast 1428","1374":"1374","1494":"1494","Bef 1400":"enne 1400","before 1429":"enne 1429","1429":"1429","1428":"1428","Aft 1429":"pärast 1429","Ellesborough, Buckinghamshire district, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ellesborough, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ellesborough, Buckinghamshire, England":"Ellesborough, Buckinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"1400–Aft 1429":"1400–1429 jälkeen","1400–1429":"1400–1429","1400–1494":"1400–1494","1429–1494":"1429–1494","1374–1428":"1374–1428","–Female":"Kuollut","1400":"1400","after 1428":"1428 jälkeen","1374":"1374","1494":"1494","Bef 1400":"ennen vuotta 1400","before 1429":"ennen vuotta 1429","1429":"1429","1428":"1428","Aft 1429":"1429 jälkeen","Ellesborough, Buckinghamshire district, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ellesborough, Buckinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ellesborough, Buckinghamshire, England":"Ellesborough, Buckinghamshire, England"},"fr":{"1400–Aft 1429":"1400–après 1